Inspector-General of Police (IGP) Usman Baba has threatened to sanction any police officer who extorts recruits in police training school. He said his administration would not encourage corrupt practices in the police force. Baba gave the warning in Abuja at a meeting with commandants of police colleges across the country. The IGP said every Nigerian from the 774 local government areas is captured in the recruitment process.   Kumuyi defends choice of speakers at youth programme     Senate probes BPE’s alleged non-remittance of $679.4m yearly…     Fed Govt: National Development Plan needs N348.1tr…   He also praised President Muhammadu Buhari for giving the approval to employ 10,000 police officers every year in the next six years. - Advertisement - Baba said: “Let me use this medium to remind you of this administration’s zero tolerance for acts of corruption or extortion of any form. Accordingly, there must be no form of extortion of the recruits by the Directing, Drill Staff or any other staff member of police colleges. “Note that (members of) the Force Management Team has our ears on the ground and any form of infraction on this directive will be visited with severe sanction and appropriate disciplinary measures. “Adequate provisions have been made by the Federal Government for the welfare of the recruits and workers of the training colleges. You are, however, expected to liaise with the commissioners of police in your respective states to ensure that adequate security arrangements are made for the protection of the colleges.”